<P>
PROPOSAL TO DOUBLE BRIDGE TOLLS FAILS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Assembly rejected a proposal to double the toll on seven state-run bridges 
in the San Francisco Bay Area -- from $1 to $2 -- to raise $200 million for 
public transit. The bill was introduced during the Legislature's special 
session to address special needs after the Oct. 17 earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
It failed on a 26-35 vote, well short of the two-thirds majority needed to 
clear the 80-member house. But Assemblyman Tom Bates (D-Berkeley) said he would 
revise his measure and bring it up again in regular session. Besides doubling 
tolls, it provides free passage for cars carrying three or more people, 
including the driver. The measure does not apply to the locally operated Golden 
Gate Bridge, which already has a $2 toll. 
</P>
</TEXT>
