<P>
ENGINEERS TRY TO PUT SATELLITE IN SAFE ORBIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Engineers at Kennedy Space Center, Fla., radioed commands to a stranded 
$150-million communications satellite to fire on-board rockets in a bid to 
boost the errant relay station into a higher, long-term storage orbit. 
</P>
<P>
If all goes well, it will reach a safe orbit sometime today, preventing an 
inadvertent re-entry into the atmosphere and providing plenty of time to devise 
a rescue plan. The National Aeronautics and Space Administration indicated that 
it would consider a rescue by a space shuttle if the satellite reaches a safe 
orbit. The Intelsat 6 satellite was stranded in a useless, lopsided orbit when 
it failed to separate properly from its Titan 3 booster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
