<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ORANGE; 
</P>
<P>
PARENTS' ROLE IN EDUCATION STRESSED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LAURA MICHAELIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 250 people turned out this week for a "Successful Parents" conference 
that included seminars on self-esteem, the dangers of steroids and gang 
violence in Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
The third annual conference emphasized the need for parental support of 
education and gave parents the chance to talk with education experts, said 
program chairwoman Jane Wyner. 
</P>
<P>
County Supervisor Gaddi H. Vasquez, keynote speaker at the Wednesday night 
gathering, said schools are increasingly emphasizing the role of the parent in 
education. 
</P>
<P>
"I think it's indicative of the growing knowledge that parents are going to be 
a critical component of developing an educational strategy for the United 
States," Vasquez said. "They (school districts) realize that they cannot 
succeed in the classroom -- they have to go beyond the classroom." While Wyner 
was pleased at the turnout for the program at Orange High School, she said such 
events don't always reach the parents of the children who need help the most. 
</P>
<P>
"What we figure is that 20% of the parents here are looking for assistance in 
some way," Wyner said. "Honestly, 80% are already magnificent parents and 
that's why they're here. But there's that 20% we catch that means everything to 
us." 
</P>
<P>
The program was sponsored by the Orange Unified School District. LAURA 
MICHAELIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
