</P>
<P>
EVANS BREAKS 2ND SWIM RECORD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
AUSTIN, Tex. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Janet Evans, who already has set an American record in the 500-yard freestyle, 
led qualifiers today in the 400 individual medley as defending champion 
Stanford made a charge at front-running Texas in the NCAA women's swimming and 
diving championships. 
</P>
<P>
No. 1-ranked Stanford trailed Texas 202 to 177 points after the first day, when 
Evans broke the oldest American record in women's swimming with a time of 4 
minutes, 34.39 seconds in the 500 Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Tracy Caulkins, formerly of Florida, held the record of 4:36.25 set 11 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
Evans, a freshman from Placentia and a three-time Olympic gold medalist in 
1988, was timed in 4:13.35 today in the preliminaries in the 400 medley. 
Caulkins also holds that American record, 4:04.63, set in 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
